msDesc.head: Jacobus de Voragine, Sermones de beata virgine; Sermon on the Trinity

p.note: Spine-liner in the form of a strip of paper with text visible underneath the pastedowns.

watermark.term: Bunch of grapes, above band with the letters PH?.

supportDesc.foliation: Medieval foliation with Arabic numerals in ink. In places where the medieval numerals could cause confusion an early-modern or modern hand has added foliation above the medieval (e.g. ). iudicis nostre et mater

collation.signatures: Quire signatures partially visible at the beginning of each new quire.
collation.catchwords: Catchwords visible on quires 12-14. The rest lost due to trimming.

p.note: Upper part of page, in brown ink by a 19th century hand: Jacobi de Voragine Speculum de Beata Virgine (Sermones CLI.); centre page: National Library stamp.

binding.p: Early modern binding. Parchment over cardboard. 5 raised bands and endbands. , in ink: SPECVLVM B. VIRGINIS IACOBI DE VORAGINE; in ink: J. de Voragine Speculum de beata Virgine; stamped in gold: A 161; ink on paper label: No 49.; ink on paper label: e. 30. 5. 8.; ink on torn paper label: 156.

origin.p: Germany? , 15th century. The origin and dating is tentatively based on the watermarks. An addition in German on (lach lieb lach) also indicates Germany.

provenance.p:
Early provenance unknown. On there is an addition dated to . Later the manuscript was acquired by Paul Petau, whose son Alexandre Petau
's signature is found on (dated to ). The manuscript was acquired from Petau by Queen Christina and brought to Sweden. Of the labels on the , 49 refers to the catalogue of 1734 (U 125e) where it is listed as Theol. in fol. no 49; e. 30. 5. 8. refers to Hammarsköld's catalogue from the 19th century (U 133). The signum 156 has not been identified.

msItem.title: Sermones de beata Virgine
msItem.rubric: Incipit speculum de beata virgine Iacobi de voragine
msItem.incipit: ABstinecia multipliciter fuit in beatissima maria virgine gloriosa
msItem.explicit: Illa tamen licet specialiter designatur que materna transfixit uiscera domino in cruce moriente Deo gracias laus deo
msItem.note: No modern edition of the text exists. It was printed in Paris 1503.

msItem.title: Sermon on the Trinity
msItem.incipit: Amen amen dico tibi quia quod scimus loquimur (John 3:11) Nos igitur alta sapientibus relinquentes humilia et plana dicamus
msItem.explicit: Synodus nycena edidit et sanctus Ieronymus ipsum in fine psalmorum decantandum instituit Rogemus et cetera Laus deo

watermark.term: Mountain with three coupaux, on top double line rod with cross.

supportDesc.foliation: Chapter numbers in red ink in the upper margin, only in some sections of the manuscript.
supportDesc.condition: Minor staining throughout. has a contemporary repair in the inner margin.

p.note: Bottom of page, in brown ink by an early modern hand: Alexander Pauli filius Petauius senator Parisiensis 1649.

Copious marginal additions by several hands. Examples: On there are Bible references in the same ink as the main text and corrections in a darker ink, both appear to be by the scribe or a contemporary hand. This type of additions appear throughout the entire manuscript. From on additions by an early modern hand start to appear. From on chapter references by a modern hand in pencil.

The entire leaf is covered by two layers of additions. Layer 1: an older medieval hand has written scattered phrases which can be read from two directions, e.g. the phrase lach lieb lach. Layer 2: a later medieval hand has covered most of the page with references to and excerpts from different books of the Bible and the Church Fathers. The first line of these additions read: Sermo feria 3a penthecostes Anno domini 1513.

decoDesc.p: Main text in black ink, rubrics in red, capitals touched in red, pilcrows in red, green, and blue.

decoNote.p: : The majority of the sermons are opened by plain initials over 2-3 lines alternating in red and green with flourishing in contrasting colour. Some of the initials feature more complex flourishing, e.g. where a face has been drawn in the counterspace (similarily on ). Around ten sermons feature larger plain initials over 5-7 lines, some of these have reserved interior space or complex flourishing, e.g. on . , : two puzzle intitials over 3-5 lines in blue and green with red flourishing. : space reserved for intial. The space reserved extends over 8 lines, but above more than half the leaf is left blank, which may indicate further decoration was intended.
